Are you putting off a passion project in your life simply due to time constraints, fear or anxiety that it won’t be good? 

My friends & I call it “the monster” because the more you avoid it, the bigger the monster becomes keeping you from taking the first step. 

Personally, I am juggling several passion projects, but what I realized recently is that doubt & fears were paralyzing any progress. So, this week I made a few decisions.  I decided to pick a project & commit. I set a “first stage” deadline & reached out to the person who wants to collab and said “I’m ready to begin.” Believe it or not, it wasn’t as scary as I thought. In fact, once I said “yes” it felt quite freeing. 

What are you postponing or kicking down the road?  My hope is that you can find the courage to begin. Just begin. You got this!!! 💪

“Be messy and complicated and afraid and show up anyways." @glennondoyle ❤️

This quote says so much about life whether at work, on stage, in a relationship or alone. We have to continue to show up even in our imperfections. 
 
This picture is from earlier this month when I served as MC for a huge event hosted by @turkishairlines  Over 200 people were in the audience and many had traveled from all around the world- places like India, Turkey, Italy & France. As a simple girl from South Carolina, I never could have imagined standing on stage alone in front of such a crowd trying to keep the pace for the evening & being myself at the same time.  Moments like these remind me that each one of us has the intelligence, grit & insight to do whatever is in front of us. - even if it’s hard. 

These days, after years of practice, I love being on stage & interacting with audiences. I delight in the simple camaraderie of it all. Seeing people laugh or cry depending on the topic & knowing that my choice to remain present helped us to create a special moment in time, feels good. 

What do you enjoy doing that surprises you?

Before I got into television news, I was a high school teacher.  The classroom was my office. These days, this studio is my office. 

I anchor 20 hours of live news every week here @ktla5news so that means I spend a lot of time inside under artificial light. 

Last week when I left work, it was beautiful outside and I thought, wow. I’m missing out on all this beauty because I’m inside all day. BUT then I changed my perspective. I instead thought, this only makes me appreciate the beauty and warmth of a sunny day even more. ☀️

Perspective is tricky. We can make some pretty bad choices depending on how we perceive our situation. This quote says it all for me. ⬇️

“We don’t see things as they are, we see them as we are.” #anaisnin 

How can you see something from a new perspective? 💜

Express it. Don’t seek it. 💜

I read this quote today doing research for an upcoming interview.  The words hit me like a ton of bricks. Think about it. We often focus on only “seeking” joy. We can become obsessed with the high that joy brings - a new car, a new job, a new lover, a trip, and even a silly number on a scale… But these are fake highs. They are temporary. The newness will fade. The joy fades every time even if only slightly. 

So what I heard in Sadhguru’s words boils down to the deeper meaning of what joy looks like. We seek it. We get it. Then soon enough we are empty again. 

Instead what brings true joy is simple in a weird way. “Expressing” joy - It’s slightly different. It feels warm. It’s magnetic - not selfish like seeking. It’s opening yourself to being vulnerable and letting love in, even if you are scared. Expressing joy means you are sharing not taking. 

I’ve been expressing my joy through dance, laughter, loving myself (flaws & all) and by living in the joy of NOW - not in the past and not in the future. I’ll keep you posted. 🌻

How do you express joy?

While I love celebrating July 4th, this day can also be very stressful due to fireworks and dog safety. 

Thousands of dogs end up in shelters or are hit by cars when they escape. In turn, dogs already at the shelters are euthanized to make room for the influx. 

Great news- @petco and @laanimalservices have partnered to help you find your lost pet or help you when you find a lost dog. 
Visit www.lost.Petcolove.org
You can also call this number 424-354-3914 for lots of help. 

Best way to help: 
Bring your pets indoors. 
Use treats to distract them. 
Play calming music. 
Leave his/her crate door open so they don’t freak out. 
Never leave a scared dog home alone. 

Thank you all for reading & maybe sharing. ❤️💙🐕❤️💙
@moosedogla says thank u too!!!! 🐾
